Study 2: T1 and correlations for hormones and SNAG

Shuying Yu

11/26/2022

Modified on: November 30th, 2022

Overview

This report provides exploratory and preliminary correlation analyses between sex hormones and T1 hippocampal ROI data extracted from AAL for the Healthy Aging Study sample that have completed spatial navigation behavior. Mask was selected for left and right hippocampus, using 2D dilation 1 on registered (not smoothed) segmented grey matter using Wake Forest Univeristy PickAtlas and MarsBaR toolboxes in SPM12.

Cleaning data steps included (T1 hipp):

  1. Filter participants that have T1 data from scan and have completed spatial

  2. Select sex hormone measures from when spatial was conducted

  3. Correct left and right volumes with TIV

  4. Average left and right volumes to get an average measure

Above table shows the table of sample size and mean and standard deviation of age by sex for overall group who have completed spatial behavior and have a T1 scan.

All sample size for T1 x hormone correlations for women are listed in the table above. For men, because some participants did not have all hormones evaluated (e.g, only testosterone available), the sample size for the correlations for that hormone and with T1 hipp volume will be different.

For men, the accurate sample sizes would be:

  • LOOP: n = 16 DHEAS, n = 18 for SHBG and T

  • MAZE: n = 21 DHEAS, n = 22 for SHBG and T

  • DSP: n = 25 DHEAS, n = 26 for SHBG and T

Structural Distributions

Shapiro-Wilks test reveals that the average T1 hipp volume for all groups (overall, women, men) were normally distributed.

Box plot shows the women appear to have greater T1 hippocampal GMV than men.

ANOVA results comparing T1 hipp GMV by reproductive status was not significant.

T-test results comparing GMV by sex was significant. Women (M = 0.556) have larger T1 hippocampal volume than men (M = 0.484) (t = 10.07, df = 63.50, p < 0.001).

T1 and Hormone

We know that estradiol, progesterone, and FSH distributions are skewed, so we can either apply log transformations or move forward with Spearman rank correlations. Despite log transformations, hormones were still significant (different than normal), so correlations will be Spearman rank correlations with raw hormone values for women.

For men, DHEAS was not normal so Spearman rank correlation will be applied for these associations with T1 hipp GMV.

Hormone Correlation by Reproductive Status

All correlations are Spearman rank. DHEAS was negatively correlated with T1 hippocampal GMV for posts (p < 0.01).

Hormone Correlation by Men

All correlations are Pearson except for DHEAS (Spearman).

T1 and Behavior

Like the overall distributions, LOOP DVs look normal but MAZE and DSP variables appear skewed.

LOOP

Position Error

All are Pearson correlations. T1 hipp GMV is postively correlated with position error for pres (p < 0.05).

Degrees Traveled

All correlations are pearson

MAZE

Accuracy

All correlations are Spearman.

Moves

All Spearman correlations.

DSP

Wayfinding Success

All correlations were pearson. Overall, lower T1 hipp GMV was associated with lower wayfinding success in DSP (p < 0.05). This pattern was also observed marginally in men (p = 0.055), but not in women (p = 0.89).

Solution Index

All correlations are spearman. For women, T1 volume is positively marginally associated with DSP solution index (p = 0.079). This pattern was also observed in pres (p = 0.068)

Summary

Results reveal that:

  • Sample included HAS participants who had a T1 scan and completed spatial navigation behavior

  • Based on structural comparisons and after correcting for TIV, women have larger T1 hippocampal volume than men (p < 0.001). Correlations between brains structure and hormones among women were carried out using Spearman rank. All correlations with men were Pearson except for DHEAS. No significant correlations between hormone concentrations and T1 hippocampal volume were observed for men. DHEAS was negatively correlated with T1 hippocampal GMV for posts (p < 0.01, Spearman).

  • For LOOP, T1 hipp GMV is positively correlated with position error for pres (p < 0.05, Pearson). Women with higher GMV correlated with lower degrees traveled (p < 0.05, Pearson). Pres who had higher GMV correlated with lower degrees traveled (p < 0.01, Pearson).

  • For MAZE, there were no significant correlations observed for men or women.

  • For DSP, overall (women and men) higher T1 hipp GMV was associated with lower wayfinding success in DSP (p < 0.05, Pearson). This pattern was also observed marginally in men (p = 0.055, Pearson), but not in women (p = 0.89, Pearson). DSP solution index was marginally positively associated with women with higher GMV (p = 0.079, Spearman). This pattern was also observed among pres (p = 0.068, Spearman)
